of pro- and anti-foie gras forces. She combines personal stories with fair-minded analysis of the social contexts within which foie gras is loved and loathed. From the barns of rural southwest France and the headquarters of the European Union in Brussels, to exclusive New York City kitchens and the government offices of Chicago, DeSoucey demonstrates that the debates over foie gras involve heated and controversial politics. Her rich and nuanced account draws our attention to the cultural dynamics of markets, the multivocal nature of "gastropolitics," and the complexities of what it means to identify as a "moral" eater in today's food world.Investigating the causes and consequences of the foie gras wars, Contested Tastes illuminates the social significance of food and taste in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCooking (Foie gras)xPolitical aspects. 0aCooking (Foie gras)xSocial aspects. 0aFoie grasxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFoie grasxPolitical aspects. 0aFoie grasxPublic opinion. 0aFoodxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aAmerican culture.  aChicago.  aFrench cuisine.  aFrench national culture.  aactivism.  aaffective relationships.  aanimal rights.  aartisanal farmers.  aconsumer culture.  acontested food.  acuisine.  acuisines.  aculinary.  acultural change.  acultural dynamics.  acultural evolution.  aethnic food traditions.  afoie gras ban.  afoie gras consumers.  afoie gras debate.  afoie gras producers.  afoie gras production.  afoie gras traditions.  afoie gras.  afood politics.  afood.  afoods.  afoodways.  agastronationalism.  agastropolitics.  aheritage.  aidentities.  ainstitutional structures.  ama